The increase in funding is offset by a surplus of Digital Platform Modernization (DPM) Phase 3 funds as a result of contracting delays, which will be reprofiled to 2025-26 and are essential to maintain momentum and deliver the full scope of the Tranche 1 and Tranche 2; as well as an internal reallocation of funds to other programs in order to meet operational priorities.

planning_explanation:
**($)**
The decrease in planned spending from 2025-26 to 2027-28 is mainly attributable to:
•	The temporary top-up funding for the Interim Federal Health Program ending in 2025-26 to manage asylum-related expenditures as the system continues to respond to elevated claim volumes;
•	The extension of funding ending in 2026-27 for the Interim Housing Assistance Program to support jurisdictions on housing-related pressures associated with heightened volumes of asylum claimants as the Department draws down its hotel operations;
•	The decrease in funding for the stabilization and integrity of Canada’s asylum system and further streamline the processing of asylum claims to allow the system to function more effectively and efficiently in the face of increased volumes;
•	The extension of funding ending in 2025-26 for the continued draw down of IRCC’s temporary accommodation operations; and
•	The department’s commitment to reduce spending as announced in Budget 2023 Refocusing Government Spending.

**($)**
The decrease in planned spending from 2025-26 to 2027-28 is mainly attributable to:
•	The temporary information technology funding ending in 2026-27 for the implementation of the Digital Platform Modernization Phase 3 Tranche 2;
•	The temporary information technology funding ending in 2025-26 for the full Tranche 1 implementation of the Digital Platform Modernization Phase 3 programme, including the implementation of front-facing capabilities for all IRCC clients to improve client experience and streamline application intake; 
•	The decrease in information technology funding for the stabilization and integrity of Canada’s asylum system and further streamline the processing of asylum claims to allow the system to function more effectively and efficiently in the face of increased volumes;
•	The decrease of information technology funding following the decision to reduce immigration levels as part of the 2025-2027 Immigration Levels Plan; and
•	The department’s commitment to reduce spending as announced in Budget 2023 Refocusing Government Spending.

**FTE**
The decrease in planned FTEs from 2026-27 to 2027-28 is mainly attributable to the temporary personnel funding ending in 2026-27 for the implementation of the Digital Platform Modernization Phase 3 Tranche 2, enabled by the procurement of a new back-end Case management Platform.

